  "opinion": "As a barista in Milan with a lower secondary education and immigrant roots, I’ve seen how stereotype threat plays out in everyday life, even outside formal education. Stereotype threat isn’t just an academic concept—it’s the quiet anxiety that lingers when someone feels their identity might be judged or dismissed. For example, when my kids ask why they can’t be engineers like their favorite teacher, I realize how deeply these stereotypes shape expectations from a young age. In STEM fields, where people often feel they don’t belong, stereotype threat can make someone second-guess their abilities, even when they’re capable. It’s not about intelligence—it’s about the fear of confirming a stereotype that’s been passed down through generations. As someone who’s struggled with depression and has a high openness to new ideas, I know that addressing this issue isn’t just about policy changes; it’s about creating spaces where people feel safe to be themselves. In my community, we’ve started small—through volunteering at science fairs for kids from immigrant families—to show that everyone has a place in STEM. But real change requires listening, not just talking. We need to challenge the narrative that STEM is only for a select few, and instead, highlight the diverse stories of those who’ve succeeded. It’s a slow process, but one that matters deeply because when we remove the stigma, we open doors for more people to thrive.",
